title: US army confirms man who murdered Denise Morgan was former soldier
text: The US army has confirmed that the man who [murdered a Louth woman at her home in New York](https://www.irishexaminer.com/news/arid-41270170.html) was a former soldier. Denise Morgan, from Tullyallen suffered a gunshot wound to the head and neck during a row with her former partner Joed A Taveras in Queens on October 21. The mother of one had ended the relationship and was preparing to move to a new apartment with her daughter when she died. When police arrived on the scene, they discovered the remains of Ms Morgan and Mr Tavaras, who had turned the gun on himself. In a statement, the US army press office told thethat Mr Tavaras held a previous position of ‚Äúspecialist‚Äù within the defence forces. ‚ÄúHe held the rank of specialist at the end of service," it said. ‚ÄúDue to Privacy Act constraints, we are unable to provide the characterization of discharge for any soldier. ‚ÄúArmy policy controls a current soldier‚Äôs access to government firearms and participation in live fire exercises but does not extend to possession of personal firearms by former soldiers." An online obituary for Mr Tavaras said he served four years as a tanker, deploying in 2013, before he was ‚Äúdishonourably discharged‚Äù. Ms Morgan‚Äôs family previously told thethat they will ‚Äúnever get justice‚Äù for Denise, but that they wanted to warn others about the dangers of controlling behaviours. Lisa Morgan said: ‚ÄúHe was trying to cut her off from people. ‚ÄúI was though, afraid of what he would do if he knew Denise was leaving. There were red flags and we knew he was controlling. But no one expected this. We just hope that people will be careful when they are leaving an abusive relationship because she was living with him for five years. You would never see this coming."

title: Warm weather wreaks havoc on some B.C. ski hills as lack of snow leaves trails barren
text:
Warm weather wreaks havoc on some B.C. ski hills as lack of snow leaves trails barren
VANCOUVER ‚Äî British Columbia‚Äôs abnormally warm winter has left local ski resorts grappling with a lack of snow during the holiday tourism season, as resorts struggle to keep runs open.
Fewer than half of Whistler Blackcomb‚Äôs trails are open, while Vancouver‚Äôs Mount Seymour is closed entirely while it waits for better conditions.
Warmth related to the El Ni√±o climate phenomenon this week has pushed temperatures to record highs in regions including Metro Vancouver, Greater Victoria, the Sunshine Coast and the Okanagan.
In Whistler, 120 kilometres north of Vancouver, Environment Canada was reporting no snow on the ground on Christmas Day, compared to 40 centimetres last Christmas.
On Thursday, the Whistler Blackcomb resort reported 117 of its 275 trails were open, as well as only 42 per cent of its terrain.
Warm weather has hit Metro Vancouver‚Äôs three main ski hills even harder, with Cypress and Grouse mountains operating only one or two runs each.
Mount Seymour closed entirely on Wednesday, Thursday and Friday, pending more snow.
James Shalman, general manager at Apex Mountain Resort in the Okanagans, says resorts across the province are ‚Äúdefinitely behind the 8-ball‚Äù because of the warm weather, with visitors lost during the holidays unlikely to return later in the season.
‚ÄúAll resorts in B.C. are very reliant on the Christmas holidays as a significant portion of their financial picture for the season,‚Äù Shalman said.
‚ÄúThis is not something where you can make up what you‚Äôre down during Christmas break. You won‚Äôt make that up later in the season, even if we get amazing snowfall in January, February, March.‚Äù
Apex on Thursday had about a third of its roughly 79 runs open, a stark contrast from 2022 when every run was open in the first week of December thanks to heavy snowfalls.
Shalman said Apex had significant snow-making capacity and used it to combat the lack of precipitation, but there were weeks this month where the temperatures were too warm to make snow.
‚ÄúI mean, we are essentially snow farmers,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre Mother Nature-dependent, and we just have to take what we get.‚Äù
At Cypress Mountain in West Vancouver, management warned skiers of ‚Äúthin snow coverage‚Äù for what little of the hill was open.
Several resorts have been offering discounted passes and tickets to entice skiers to visit.
‚ÄúRain‚Äôs the star of the show today,‚Äù Cypress Mountain‚Äôs update on Thursday said, noting that night skiing had been cancelled.
Environment Canada meteorologist Brian Proctor said that in addition to El Ni√±o, a ridge of high pressure had created a ‚Äúblocking pattern‚Äù across much of North America. That was preventing the warm air generated by El Ni√±o from passing over mountains and continuing inland.
Proctor said it meant the warm air mass had lingered over B.C., unable to go east due to high pressure acting like ‚Äúa wall.‚Äù
He said Environment Canada‚Äôs long-term forecast called for more seasonal temperatures to return for the first week of January, bringing potential snowfall to higher elevations in the Interior.
But Proctor said snowfall was less certain for coastal areas in coming weeks, adding that skiers and resorts should temper expectations.
‚ÄúWe may see potential for some snowfall,‚Äù Proctor says. ‚ÄúBut really longer term it does look like an El Ni√±o winter at this point in time, continuing and remaining fairly significant into the early spring.‚Äù
This report by The Canadian Press was first published Dec. 29, 2023.
Chuck Chiang, The Canadian Press

text: In an era marked by technological advancements, the quest for securing our homes and businesses has led to the evolution of surveillance systems. Understanding CCTV (Closed-Circuit Television) While traditional CCTV systems have long been a mainstay in the security industry, modern solutions like the [Best SimpliSafe Indoor Camera](https://www.arsalpro.com/best-simplisafe-indoor-camera-reviews) reviews are gaining prominence. These advanced systems offer wireless connectivity, high-resolution feeds, and smart features, providing a new dimension to home security. However, the reliability of CCTV remains unparalleled, making it a steadfast choice in critical environments like banks, government facilities, and industrial complexes. Key Features of CCTV Security Cameras: - Reliability: Wired connections make CCTV systems highly reliable, ensuring uninterrupted surveillance. - Stability: Immune to wireless interference, CCTV cameras provide a stable and consistent video feed. - Customization: Easy to scale and customize, allowing for the addition of more cameras and features as needed. - Durability: Wired connections are less susceptible to environmental factors, enhancing the durability of CCTV systems. - Security: With a closed system, the risk of hacking or unauthorized access is significantly reduced. Understanding Wireless Security Cameras Wireless security cameras, on the other hand, have gained popularity for their flexibility and ease of installation. These cameras utilize Wi-Fi or other wireless technologies to transmit video signals, eliminating the need for extensive cabling. This makes them a popular choice for residential areas, small businesses, and locations where running cables may be challenging or impractical. Key Features of Wireless Security Cameras: - Flexibility: Wireless cameras are easy to install and relocate, providing flexibility in choosing surveillance locations. - Cost-Effective Installation: No need for extensive cabling reduces installation costs, making wireless systems more budget-friendly. - Remote Access: Many wireless cameras offer remote monitoring capabilities, allowing users to view footage from anywhere with an internet connection. - Scalability: Wireless systems can be easily expanded without the need for additional cabling, making them scalable to evolving security needs. - Quick Deployment: Ideal for temporary surveillance needs or events, wireless cameras can be quickly deployed and dismantled [.](https://businessfig.com/) CCTV vs. Wireless: A Comparative Analysis Now, let‚Äôs delve into a side-by-side comparison of CCTV and wireless security cameras based on essential factors: |Features||CCTV Security Cameras||Wireless Security Cameras| |Reliability||Highly reliable with stable wired connections.||Dependent on the strength and stability of Wi-Fi.| |Installation||Requires cabling, potentially more complex.||Simple installation without the need for cables.| |Flexibility||Less flexible due to wired connections.||Highly flexible with easy relocation options.| |Cost||Initial installation costs may be higher.||Generally more cost-effective in installation.| |Scalability||Scalable but may require additional cabling.||Easily scalable without the need for cabling.| |Remote Access||Limited without additional network configurations.||Remote access is a standard feature.| |Durability||More durable in harsh environmental conditions.||Susceptible to environmental factors.| Choosing the Right Security Camera The choice between CCTV and wireless security cameras, including those highlighted in [Best SimpliSafe Indoor Camera ](https://www.arsalpro.com/best-simplisafe-indoor-camera-reviews)reviews, hinges on individual requirements, budget considerations, and the intended application. In scenarios where steadfast reliability is crucial, especially in high-security zones, CCTV systems remain a favored option. On the other hand, for situations that demand flexibility, rapid deployment, and cost-effectiveness, wireless security cameras, with insights from comprehensive reviews, emerge as a compelling solution. It‚Äôs worth noting that hybrid solutions combining both wired and wireless technologies are also available, providing the best of both worlds. These systems leverage the stability of CCTV where needed while incorporating the flexibility of wireless cameras in other areas. In Conclusion In the ever-evolving landscape of security technology, the choice between CCTV and wireless security cameras is not a one-size-fits-all decision. Each type has its unique set of advantages and considerations, catering to different requirements and scenarios.
